Yes. I think we're largely in agreement about the benefits of removing `interface{}`. Just want to offer one point of disagreement and see what yinz think.

However, Teams are only supported by the HTTP backend. So this field would be zero'd in other implementers of `Backend`. My issue is that it's a common footgun in Go to have zeroed, uninitialized state that's indistinguishable from initialized state. I'm leaning on the "make illegal states unrepresentable" philosophy here. In a functional language, we could distinguish between `Option<[]string>` and `[]string` for this case, where `Some([]string{})` represents provided but empty array (useful for the HTTP backend) and `None` represents "Not supported". In Go, we can't really implement this pattern (some gophers use `*[]string` in this case but that's asking for a null-pointer deref.)

I'd like to lean on the "[accept interfaces and return structs](https://subscription.packtpub.com/book/programming/9781838647940/7/ch07lvl1sec45/accepting-interfaces-and-returning-structs)" methodology here:

```golang
package backend

type CreateStackOptions interface {
  SupportsTeams() bool
  Teams() []string
}

type Backend interface {
  // ...

  CreateStack(
	ctx context.Context, stackRef backend.StackReference, opts CreateStackOptions) (backend.Stack, error)
}
```

which I think is idiomatic.

