@gjc13 , very good catch!

I fully agree with @simonlingoogle . `OT_ASSERT()` is not good here and the code here should be general.

I think would be even simpler to set the `message` at the start of this method instead of in `VerifyOrExit()` 
- In general, I feel using braces `{ }` in `VerifyOrExit()` make it less readable, and better to use `if() { ....;  ExitNow(); }` for this. 

Here is my suggestion for the change:
```c++
Error Ip6::HandlePayload(Message &          aMessage,
                         MessageInfo &      aMessageInfo,
                         uint8_t            aIpProto,
                         Message::Ownership aMessageOwnership)
{
    Error    error   = kErrorNone;
    Message *message = (aMessageOwnership == Message::kTakeCustody) ? &aMessage : nullptr;

    VerifyOrExit(aIpProto == kProtoUdp || aIpProto == kProtoIcmp6);

    if (message == nullptr) // `aMessageOwnership` is `kCopyToUse`
    {
        VerifyOrExit((message = aMessage.Clone()) != nullptr, error = kErrorNoBufs);
    }
```

Basically we set the `message` at the top of the method based on the `aMessageOwnership` and then do the `VerifyOrExit()` check. If we see `message` is `nullptr` it indicates we need to copy.

