If I understand, the issue this is trying to address is that when we lower the learning rate, the code also kicks a bunch of values out of `previous_loss_values`, which then forces `loss_increased_since_last_disk_sync()` to return `false` for a while no matter what. I agree that that's not great and `loss_increased_since_last_disk_sync()` shouldn't ever be inhibited.

I think we can make this code a lot simpler though.  Recall that the reason lowering the learning rate kicked values out of `previous_loss_values` was just to prevent the learning rate from being immediately lowered again based on the same analysis of `previous_loss_values`. That was a crude way of doing it.  So rather than adding `additional_previous_loss_values_to_keep_until_disk_sync` and all the attendant extra logic, how about when the loss stalls we don't kick any values out of `previous_loss_values` but instead just update a counter that is used to measure the number of steps since the last time we lowered the learning rate.  That counter can then be used to inhibit execution of the code at line 800, by changing it from this:
```
                if (gradient_check_budget > iter_without_progress_thresh && learning_rate_shrink != 1)
 ```
to something like this:
```
                if (gradient_check_budget > iter_without_progress_thresh && learning_rate_shrink != 1 && steps_since_last_learning_rate_shrink > iter_without_progress_thresh)
 ```

This also means the code below there that does this:
```
                            // Empty out some of the previous loss values so that steps_without_progress 
                            // will decrease below iter_without_progress_thresh.  
                            for (unsigned long cnt = 0; cnt < previous_loss_values_dump_amount+iter_without_progress_thresh/10 && previous_loss_values.size() > 0; ++cnt)
                                previous_loss_values.pop_front();
```
would be replaced with something like 
```
steps_since_last_learning_rate_shrink -= previous_loss_values_dump_amount+iter_without_progress_thresh/10;
```

