@abtink What you observed is correct. You need to wait for the "Established" callback before sending data on the connection.

This isn't fundamental and it can be changed, though I'd like to test it first. The original FreeBSD code supported "implied connect" --- if you call `sendto` on a socket that isn't connected, it will establish the connection and then deliver the data. Adding data to the socket before the connection is established could be written to follow those same code paths.

With TCP Fast Open (currently in progress) this will no longer be an issue.

This has nothing to do with 3.11, but when I added the Pyhton checks to tox it started failing. The root cause is that the `has_side_effect_of` decorator dynamically injects the `return_value` kwarg into the function call to any side-effect function, but the function can ignore this - so it may / may not appear in the signature. Instead of forcing all side-effects to have identical signatures, this now removes `return_value` from the signature, so:

```python
@is_side_effect_of("baz")
def foo(arg1: str, **kwargs) -> None:
    pass
```
is considered identical to:
```python
@is_side_effect_of("baz")
def bar(arg1: str, return_value: str, **kwargs) -> None:
    pass
```

