@frenck brand logos pretty much always add valuable information.  As much as you'd like to think of it as a pure decoration, you won't find any a11y analysts, graphic designers, marketing folks, etc. to take that same stance.  Companies spend big money to design them and plaster them everywhere for a reason.

So then the context needs to be considered when choosing the alternative text, and in this case a conundrum is created because it's questionably redundant and conveys information that doesn't match the table header.  Kept as is, I think `alt=""` is the best approach because of the cognitive confusion it would create to give it anything else.

And if it would be confusing to an alternative text consumer, then it will probably be confusing to others as well.  If I'm scanning a list of my devices and there's a graphic next to the name, I'd expect that it would be a picture of the device or at least the device brand.  And if I go to the entities list, am I also going to see the integration icon or the specific icon I chose for the entity?

@piitaya thanks, that's helpful context.  I think that just reinforces that the fallback should be the manufacturer logo though and not the integration, in which case the redundancy and position issues are lessened to a great degree.

Platform API is a boundary between OT library and external modules. We could use `OPENTHREAD_CONFIG_KEY_REFERENCES_ENABLE` to clarify which field in the union is valid like:

```
OT_TOOL_PACKED_BEGIN
struct otMacKeyMaterial
{
    union
    {
#if OPENTHREAD_CONFIG_KEY_REFERENCES_ENABLE
        otMacKeyRef mKeyRef; ///< Reference to the key stored.
#elif
        otMacKey    mKey;    ///< Key stored as literal.
#endif
    } mKeyMaterial;
} OT_TOOL_PACKED_END;
```

But it is prone to errors, because OpenThread library might be compiled with other preprocessor flags than radio.c implementation.

Using `otPlatCryptoGetType` inside radio.c implementation would do the trick:

```
if (otPlatCryptoGetType() == CRYPTO_USING_KEY_REF) {
  // do something with keyMaterial.mKeyRef;
} else {
  // do something with keyMaterial.mKey;
}
```

But it looks it creates circular dependency (crypto platform depends on radio platform, and radio depends on crypto platform) what is an anti-pattern.

I think it would be better to add explicit information if key material passed to given function includes key reference or key literal like:

```
enum macKeyMaterialType {
  MAC_KEY_MATERIAL_LITERAL,
  MAC_KEY_MATERIAL_REFERENCE,
};

struct {
  const otMacKeyMaterial *mAesKey; ///< The key material used for AES-CCM frame security.
  enum macKeyMaterialType mAesKeyMaterialType;
  ...
} mTxInfo;

void otPlatRadioSetMacKey(otInstance *            aInstance,
                          uint8_t                 aKeyIdMode,
                          uint8_t                 aKeyId,
                          const otMacKeyMaterial *aPrevKey,
                          const otMacKeyMaterial *aCurrKey,
                          const otMacKeyMaterial *aNextKey,
                          enum macKeyMaterialType aKeyMaterialType);
```

